[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1230},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F29\u002Freact-day-15-usereducer\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F29\u002Freact-day-15-usereducer\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F29\u002Freact-day-15-usereducer\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F29\u002Freact-day-15-usereducer\u002F":1206,"related:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F09\u002F29\u002Freact-day-15-usereducer\u002F":1215},"\u002Freact\u002F20220929\u002F2239393703\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1189,"date":1190,"description":1191,"extension":1192,"lang":1193,"meta":1194,"navigation":585,"path":1195,"readingMinutes":1196,"seo":1197,"standalone":1198,"stem":1199,"tags":1200,"tldr":1203,"updated":1190,"url":1204,"__hash__":1205},"content\u002Fen\u002FReact\u002Freact-day-15-usereducer.md","React Day 15: useReducer — useState's Grown-Up Cousin","1002930033",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1184},"minimark",[11,16,38,41,67,73,89,101,110,118,144,147,153,172,178,185,227,230,244,264,288,362,381,434,441,494,505,517,533,548,700,705,711,738,865,870,876,885,901,1149,1154,1162,1166,1169,1180],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19,20,24,25,27,28,31,32,34,35,37],"p",{},"Next up we're going to meet something kind of special: ",[21,22,23],"code",{},"useReducer",". You can think of ",[21,26,23],{}," as a grown-up version of ",[21,29,30],{},"useState",", because when you're dealing with complicated state, ",[21,33,23],{}," lets you manage it way more cleanly — instead of cramming everything into a single variable like you do with ",[21,36,30],{},".",[12,39,23],{"id":40},"usereducer",[17,42,43,44,46,47,49,50,52,53,60,61,66],{},"Like I said in the intro, ",[21,45,23],{}," is basically the advanced version of ",[21,48,30],{},". In short, ",[21,51,23],{}," is really close to how Redux works (Redux is a library for managing data\u002Fstate, kind of like Vue's ",[54,55,59],"a",{"href":56,"rel":57},"https:\u002F\u002Fvuex.vuejs.org\u002Fzh\u002Fguide\u002F",[58],"nofollow","Vuex"," or ",[54,62,65],{"href":63,"rel":64},"https:\u002F\u002Fpinia.vuejs.org\u002F",[58],"Pinia"," — don't worry if you have no idea what those are, I'm just mentioning them in passing).",[17,68,69,70,72],{},"Alright, let's start by looking at the ",[21,71,23],{}," syntax:",[74,75,80],"pre",{"className":76,"code":77,"language":78,"meta":79,"style":79},"language-jsx shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, initialState, init);\n","jsx","",[21,81,82],{"__ignoreMap":79},[83,84,87],"span",{"class":85,"line":86},"line",1,[83,88,77],{},[17,90,91,92,94,95,97,98,100],{},"It looks a lot like ",[21,93,30],{},", but ",[21,96,23],{}," takes three arguments, whereas ",[21,99,30],{}," only takes one:",[74,102,104],{"className":76,"code":103,"language":78,"meta":79,"style":79},"const [state, dispatch] = useState(initialState);\n",[21,105,106],{"__ignoreMap":79},[83,107,108],{"class":85,"line":86},[83,109,103],{},[17,111,112,113,117],{},"So you can clearly tell these two Hooks are different (",[114,115,116],"del",{},"obviously",").",[17,119,120,121,123,124,127,128,131,132,135,136,138,139,141,142,37],{},"Now let's look at the arguments inside ",[21,122,23],{},": ",[21,125,126],{},"reducer",", ",[21,129,130],{},"initialState",", and ",[21,133,134],{},"init",". We'll set ",[21,137,134],{}," aside for now since it's optional, so we only need to focus on ",[21,140,126],{}," and ",[21,143,130],{},[17,145,146],{},"Quick side note — the React docs actually have a line about this:",[148,149,150],"blockquote",{},[17,151,152],{},"An alternative to useState. Accepts a reducer of type (state, action) => newState, and returns the current state paired with a dispatch method.",[17,154,155,156,158,159,161,162,164,165,168,169,37],{},"It's a little hard to parse, but the gist is that ",[21,157,23],{}," is just another flavor of ",[21,160,30],{}," (the variant I mentioned earlier). So when ",[21,163,23],{}," returns, it also hands you back an array — the first element is ",[21,166,167],{},"state"," and the second is ",[21,170,171],{},"dispatch",[17,173,174,175,177],{},"So how do you actually use ",[21,176,23],{},"? Let's look at an example.",[17,179,180,181,184],{},"First, declare an initial ",[21,182,183],{},"State",":",[74,186,190],{"className":187,"code":188,"language":189,"meta":79,"style":79},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","const initialState = {\n  count: 0,\n};\n","js",[21,191,192,209,221],{"__ignoreMap":79},[83,193,194,198,202,205],{"class":85,"line":86},[83,195,197],{"class":196},"sOudu","const",[83,199,201],{"class":200},"stw71"," initialState",[83,203,204],{"class":196}," =",[83,206,208],{"class":207},"s8XSl"," {\n",[83,210,212,215,218],{"class":85,"line":211},2,[83,213,214],{"class":207},"  count: ",[83,216,217],{"class":200},"0",[83,219,220],{"class":207},",\n",[83,222,224],{"class":85,"line":223},3,[83,225,226],{"class":207},"};\n",[17,228,229],{},"Note that the initial state is usually an object.",[17,231,232,233,235,236,238,239,141,241,37],{},"Next, declare a function called ",[21,234,126],{},". Notice that ",[21,237,126],{}," receives two arguments: ",[21,240,167],{},[21,242,243],{},"action",[74,245,247],{"className":76,"code":246,"language":78,"meta":79,"style":79},"const reducer = (state, action) => {\n  \u002F\u002F ...\n}\n",[21,248,249,254,259],{"__ignoreMap":79},[83,250,251],{"class":85,"line":86},[83,252,253],{},"const reducer = (state, action) => {\n",[83,255,256],{"class":85,"line":211},[83,257,258],{},"  \u002F\u002F ...\n",[83,260,261],{"class":85,"line":223},[83,262,263],{},"}\n",[17,265,266,267,269,270,273,274,276,277,279,280,283,284,287],{},"Inside this ",[21,268,126],{}," function you'll usually reach for a ",[21,271,272],{},"switch"," statement, using the ",[21,275,24